<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 11 日星期五 03:09:21 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[We’re in an Age of Fire]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>毛伊岛的野火再次证明世界必须面对“火新世”的黎明。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/vl5F8lKPa-ARuqRjEKl7ycVifBY=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/fire_age_/original.jpg" alt="大火烧毁了烟雾缭绕的大地，一架直升机在头顶飞过。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大卫麦克纽/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><em>更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日东部时间晚上 9:15</em></small><br><br>几天前，飓风预报看起来不错。朵拉要去<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mauinow.com/2023/08/06/cat-4-hurricane-dora-on-track-to-pass-well-south-of-hawai%CA%BBi-over-the-next-several-days/">遥远的南方</a>，想念夏威夷。然而，这场风暴最终还是对岛屿造成了严重破坏，不是作为降雨的气旋，而是作为风——炎热、干燥的风，当它吹过毛伊岛时，遇到了野火。<br><br>无风的情况下火灾相对容易控制；大风天发生火灾，尤其是在附近有城镇的干燥山区，对消防员来说是最糟糕的情况。事实也是如此。大火于周二开始燃烧，到那天晚上，火势已到达旅游中心拉海纳，最终将其烧毁。电源被切断了； 911 坠毁了。居民们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coast-guard-rescued-14-took-shelter-ocean-maui-wildfire-rcna99163">游进凉爽的海洋来躲避大火</a>。到目前为止，至少有53人死亡。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hawaii-wildfires-warning-climate-change/674974/">阅读：夏威夷是一个警告</a><br><br>就人员伤亡和建筑物烧毁而言，这是夏威夷现代历史上最严重的野火事件。这是该州版本的加州 2018 年营火；我采访过的专家还将此次火灾与希腊罗德岛最近发生的火灾以及 2017 年加利福尼亚州索诺玛发生的火灾进行了比较，该火灾蔓延到了圣罗莎市。毛伊岛大火再次提醒我们，我们已经进入了火灾时代——名誉教授兼野火专家斯蒂芬·J·派恩（Stephen J. Pyne） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-pyrocene-how-we-created-an-age-of-fire-and-what-happens-next-stephen-j-pyne/9780520383586?affiliate_id=atl-347">称之为</a>“火新世”。人类仍在思考如何在这个新现实中生活，在我们周围的世界在燃烧时迎头赶上。<br><br>尽管火灾是许多景观的自然组成部分——并且已经存在了几个世纪——但火灾和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/wildfire-smoke-brain-health/674336/">烟雾科学</a>的某些领域还处于相对初级阶段。火灾中大规模疏散的最佳实践<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/07/wildfire-evacuation-plans-california-alaska/670969/">仍然不存在</a>；毛伊岛副州长表示， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/wind-fanned-fires-raze-parts-hawaii-forcing-evacuations-2023-08-09/">由于停电，毛伊岛的疏散工作变得更加复杂</a>。夏威夷大学马诺阿分校的消防专家克莱·特劳尼希特 (Clay Trauernicht) 表示，夏威夷与加利福尼亚州等火灾多发州没有相同的野火历史，这意味着准备工作较少。他对该州火灾的两个潜在促成因素表示特别担忧： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/08/10/us/wildfires-maui-hawaii/hawaii-used-to-be-covered-with-plantations-the-grass-replacing-them-is-a-fire-hazard?smid=url-share">陈旧、维护不善的前</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/08/10/us/wildfires-maui-hawaii/hawaii-used-to-be-covered-with-plantations-the-grass-replacing-them-is-a-fire-hazard?smid=url-share">种植园</a>和增加燃料负荷的非本地植物物种。<br><br>一般来说，死亡的植被会引发火灾。在毛伊岛，灌木丛大火蔓延到建筑密集的地区，那里的房屋和其他建筑物助长了火势； 2017 年索诺玛县塔布斯火灾期间也出现了类似的情况。“一旦你从着火的建筑物转到另一座建筑物，你就无能为力了，”Trauernicht 告诉我。我问他这是否是夏威夷为未来更强烈的野火做好准备的警钟。 “如果不是，说实话，我不知道会发生什么，”他回答道。<br><br>美国国家气象局檀香山预报办公室的气象学家伊恩·莫里森告诉我，每年这个时候在夏威夷看到火灾天气（炎热、干燥、多风的天气）并不罕见。国家气象局已对该地区发出危险信号警告， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/04/14/1169979511/red-flag-warning-fire-prevention-tips">这向当地居民和官员表明野火的可能性很高</a>。据美国干旱监测机构称，毛伊岛大部分地区也异常干燥或处于干旱状态；西边尤其干燥，随时可能着火。<br><br>您可能认为朵拉可以缓解这些情况：飓风通常意味着水，而潮湿的东西不容易燃烧。但即使是这种动态也在发生变化。夏威夷大学马诺阿分校的研究人员进行的一项调查发现，2018 年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2020/07/22/hurricane-lane-fire-rain/">飓风莱恩同时给夏威夷带来了火灾和降雨</a>，使应急响应变得更加复杂——干燥和多风的条件使火势在风暴边缘蔓延，而在其他地方，降雨导致山体滑坡。 2020 年，研究人员指出，莱恩只是有记录的三个飓风加剧野火风险的案例之一。有了朵拉，我们可能会有第四个。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/wildfires-climate-change-impact/674381/">阅读：气候变化正在烧毁加州的明确迹象</a><br><br>预计气候变化将使飓风和热带风暴在未来几年变得更加严重，并有可能引发一系列自然灾害（干旱、野火、风暴），并相互影响。它还被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/wildfires-climate-change-impact/674381/">证明会加剧火灾</a>。过去五年里，不寻常的火灾行为故事层出不穷： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/smoke-canada-fires-how-long-months/674601/">加拿大以前所未有的速度燃烧</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/08/alaska-2022-wildfire-season-lightning/671212/">阿拉斯加苔原前所未有地冒着浓烟</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/colorado/news/boulder-county-marshall-fire-two-fires-xcel-energy/">科罗拉多州 2021 年 12 月发生的大火</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-10-06/the-frightening-implications-california-first-million-acre-wildfire">加利福尼亚州难以想象的 100 万英亩火灾</a>，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://34c031f8-c9fd-4018-8c5a-4159cdff6b0d-cdn-endpoint.azureedge.net/-/media/calfire-website/our-impact/fire-statistics/featured-items/top20_deadliest.pdf?rev=e201e407ab6943c7854c7c917c7b818b&amp;hash=8068F655A48FC601C6E2F55F9E0A1682">有记录以来最严重的火灾</a>所有这些都在几年内相继发生。<br><br> 《<em>我们的最后警告：六度气候紧急情况》</em>一书的作者马克·莱纳斯告诉我：“不同类型的气候灾难都相互加剧。” “这一切都反映了这样一个事实：随着世界变暖，系统中的能量越来越多。水蒸发得更快；风刮得更大了；火势变得更猛烈。”<br><br>莱纳斯则告诉我，他没有考虑过这种特殊的动态：“我从未想到飓风与野火之间存在联系。事实上，它只是表明了气候变暖可能带来的各种意外。”毛伊岛大火可能给夏威夷敲响了警钟。但也许它们也可以为我们其他人敲响警钟，这是近年来的众多警钟之一。火灾时代正在我们周围肆虐。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 22:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/maui-wildfire-hurricane-connection/674982/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/maui-wildfire-hurricane-connection/674982/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic Joins Forces With PBS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与杰弗里·戈德堡对话<em>《大西洋月刊》华盛顿周</em><br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/4rRZX9XRNbDlWojOTVbXddSf5UI=/0x103:1981x1217/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/WashingtonWeek_JeffreyGoldberg_AnchorDesk-1/original.jpg" alt="杰弗里·戈德堡在《大西洋月刊华盛顿周》片场" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>迈克·摩根</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br><i>大西洋报</i>的<i> </i>主编杰弗里·戈德堡 (Jeffrey Goldberg) 是 PBS 节目<i>《华盛顿周刊》</i>的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/press-releases/archive/2023/08/editor-chief-jeffrey-goldberg-named-moderator-washington-week/674893/">新主持人</a>，该节目现更名为<i>《大西洋月刊华盛顿周刊》</i> 。我与 Jeff 讨论了这一新的合作伙伴关系，该合作伙伴关系将于明天晚上 8 点（美国东部时间）在 PBS 上推出。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的四个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hawaii-wildfires-warning-climate-change/674974/">夏威夷是一个警告。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/aristotle-10-rules-happy-life/674905/">亚里士多德美好生活的10条规则</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/grief-digital-assets-posthumous-technology/674964/">“我妈妈去世后会给我发电子邮件。”</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/trump-twitter-account-special-counsel-search-warrant/674969/">永远不要发推文。</a></li><strong>对民主的关注</strong><br><br><b>汤姆·尼科尔斯：</b> <i>《华盛顿周刊》</i>和<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>本身就是机构。将他们联合起来开展这样一个项目的目标是什么？也许我不应该说“像这样的程序”，而应该先问你设想什么样的程序。<br><br><b>杰弗里·戈德堡：</b>我的目标是我认为<i>《华盛顿周》</i>已经做得非常好的事情：我想与实际报道本周事件的记者进行讨论，以便观众不仅了解正在发生的事情，而且了解正在发生的事情。这些故事是如何报道的。我们需要时间与在场的人进行更详细的对话，他们会告诉我们发生了什么。这个程序的一大优点是它允许人们在整个段落中说话，而我是段落的忠实粉丝。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>这对你来说是一个新的演出，对吧？你从来没有当过主持人。<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>对。我已经参加过数以百万计的电视和会议专题讨论会——唉，我再也回不去了——但这是我第一次担任主持人。所以我的建议是你看一下，看看我是否能够从提词器中读出内容。这个问题尚无定论。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>既然你要坐在办公桌的<i>另</i>一边，你打算如何主持这个节目呢？格式会是什么样子？<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>我讨厌让事情听起来如此简单，因为，如你所知，我是一个复杂的人。但这里的目标是找到媒体中最优秀的人才，让他们分析正在发生的事情。我希望人们在观看此内容后感觉自己确实学到了一些东西。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>嗯，我认为这并不简单，但这听起来像是对有线电视时代之前更古老、更具对话性的新闻节目传统的回调。<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>从某种程度上来说，确实如此。一些电视新闻和公共事务节目已经变得过于狂热，不合我的口味。在简短的片段中，观众会受到灯光和蜂鸣器的轰炸，其中有六七个人或更多的人试图尽快阐明观点。其中一些人是党派黑客。现在电视上很少有一群记者进行真正的对话，我们将花时间进行更耐心的对话。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>但这不就是观众想要的——闪光和运动吗？<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>看，这个国家有很多人。有些人想要 TikTok；有些人想要 TikTok；有些人想要 TikTok。有些人想要<i>《大西洋月刊》</i> 。有些人两者都想要。不一定是你或我——当然，尽管你是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@theatlantic/video/7166692270241090859">TikTok 明星</a>。但我确信存在维恩重叠。在<i>大西洋</i>，<i> </i>我们知道我们的读者有很强的注意力。 <i>《华盛顿周刊》</i>和<i>PBS NewsHour</i>的观众也是如此。看看有多少人会听长播客、阅读长文章。我们将针对该计划提供足够的空间来进行详细讨论。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>等我把我的猫带上 TikTok 再说吧。但回到电视上，这种狂热的活动在很大程度上是由党派之争驱动的。这些节目邀请党派拥护者在五分钟内就复杂的问题进行决斗，尽管我在这方面并非没有罪恶，但我同意这可能会让人发疯。尽管如此，选举即将到来，人们将关注 2024 年。 <i>《大西洋月刊华盛顿周刊》</i>将如何应对这将是相当奇怪的一年？<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>今年不仅是奇怪的一年，而且也是奇怪的一年。这是美国历史上独一无二的选举。一名受到州和联邦起诉的前总统正在与击败他的人进行竞选，他最终可能会入狱或入主白宫。但<i>《华盛顿周刊》</i>和<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>都是无党派的。<i>大西洋报</i>的<i> </i>我们的座右铭是“不属于任何党派或派系”——但我们确实非常关心美国理念、民主及其生存，我想将对民主的关注从<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>带到<i>《华盛顿周刊》</i> 。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>你将主要与来自媒体的其他人交谈，而人们非常不信任记者。你认为这对于节目来说是一个问题吗？<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>公众不信任很多机构，尤其是记者，是的。我们生活在一个很多人都往别人最坏的方面想的时代。这种不信任使得人们很难及时了解情况，这对民主不利。这就是为什么不仅报道故事很重要，而且向观众解释这些故事<i>是如何</i>报道的也很重要。<br><br><b>汤姆：</b>你是已故格温·伊菲尔的朋友，他帮助<i>《华盛顿周刊》</i>成为一个机构。通过观察她，你学到了什么？<br><br><b>杰夫：</b>格温相信新闻业，她相信存在可观察到的现实，她不害怕任何事或任何人，她相信美国的承诺。她是有史以来最伟大的人之一。她拥有这样的权威，部分原因是她知道真相，并相信她有重要的工作要做。它还来自于作为一个先驱者，作为一个黑人女性，这个行业并不总是对改变、对其他声音开放感兴趣。她确实是我的英雄之一，作为朋友，我每天都想念她。她在特朗普当选后不久就去世了，在过去的七年里，这个国家真的可以利用她的技能、洞察力和无畏精神。<br><br><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>厄瓜多尔总统候选人费尔南多·比亚维森西奥（Fernando Villavicencio）曾直言不讳地批评政府腐败，他在昨天晚上的一次集会上<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/09/world/americas/ecuador-presidential-candidate-killed.html">被暗杀</a>。</li><li> <a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/clarence-thomas-other-billionaires-sokol-huizenga-novelly-supreme-court">ProPublica 的一份新报告</a>发现，最高法院法官克拉伦斯·托马斯接受了富裕赞助人提供的礼物和招待，数量比之前已知的要多，但未能披露其中一些。</li><li>朝鲜官方媒体报道称，金正恩已<a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/-kim-jong-un-fires-general-north-korea-war-plans-military-rcna99171">解除其最高将领的职务</a>，并命令军队加强战争准备。</li><b>晚读</b><br><br>猫头鹰并不像它们看起来的那样<br><br><em>丽贝卡·吉格斯</em><br><br><p>在看到猫头鹰之前的那一刻，会有一种类似直觉的感觉。我不会忘记有一天晚上，当我站在悉尼郊区的阳台上时，周围丛林中每一个清醒的生物都突然冻结了。就连青蛙似乎也想放弃它们吵闹的身体。<i>谁去那里？</i>几秒钟后，一只强大的猫头鹰（澳大利亚本土物种的名称）落在栏杆上，我也差点从皮肤上跳下来。猫头鹰有梗犬那么大，但像刚放了一天的聚酯薄膜气球一样懒洋洋地漂浮着，在我耳中听着很安静。在针落的寂静中，它沿着栏杆弹跳。我从未听说过它的爪子接触到金属。我知道，猫头鹰本身的听力非常敏锐，它能听出负鼠皮毛下心脏的跳动。看不见的，第二只猫头鹰——我猜是第一只猫头鹰的伴侣——发出了低沉的木管叫声。</p><p>猫头鹰的叫声通常看起来像幽灵或未成熟的声音。双重魔法：猫头鹰可以让我们怀疑自己的能力，同时让我们对它们的奥秘感到好奇。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/owl-senses-smart-animal-intelligence/674769/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/britain-honors-system-peerage-lords/674963/">丑闻将同行推入深渊</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/espn-sports-betting-mobile-gambling/674967/">体育博彩赢了。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/us-saudi-israel-normalization-deal/674973/">以色列与沙特的协议最好是一份好的协议。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/08/photos-deadly-wildfires-sweep-across-maui/674970/">照片：致命的野火席卷毛伊岛。</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>听。</b>人工智能可以拯救生命吗？在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/08/are-ai-relationships-real/674965/"><i>大西洋广播电台</i>的最新一集中</a>，主持人汉娜·罗辛和制片人伊桑·布鲁克斯讨论了一个在最黑暗的时刻求助于人工智能伴侣的人。<br><br><b>手表。</b> <i>《红、白、宝蓝》</i> （在 Amazon Prime Video 上播放）是一种逃避现实的幻想，无论如何努力<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/red-white-and-royal-blue-movie-review/674971/">都无法完全逃离现实世界</a>。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br> <i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 21:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/atlantic-pbs-washington-week/674980/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/atlantic-pbs-washington-week/674980/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Israeli-Saudi Deal Had Better Be a Good One]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以色列和沙特阿拉伯关系正常化将是一个重大突破，但不惜任何代价。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/aXy509xc3ed2hh4V-eMRDhyZL5c=/0x0:2500x1406/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_1241919563/original.jpg" alt="2022 年 7 月 15 日，美国总统乔·拜登（右）在沙特阿拉伯吉达的阿尔萨拉姆皇宫会见沙特阿拉伯王储穆罕默德·本·萨勒曼（左）。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>沙特阿拉伯皇家宫廷/阿纳多卢通讯社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>过去几周，以色列和美国官员暗示可能达成以色列和沙特阿拉伯关系正常化的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Furl%3Fq%3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2Furl%3Fq%253Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Fu-s-saudi-arabia-agree-to-broad-terms-for-israel-normalization-ac6d549c%3Fmod%25253Dhp_lead_pos6%2526amp%3Bsa%253DD%2526amp%3Bsource%253Deditors%2526amp%3Bust%253D1691629773501166%2526amp%3Busg%253DAOvVaw0a-fPcT8015nXugZyfna3n%26sa%3DD%26source%3Ddocs%26ust%3D1691629773512457%26usg%3DAOvVaw1KN73H8hlvK11GmMjsdf1l&amp;data=05%7C01%7Candrew.exum%40hakluytandco.com%7Cb47d82897c304581109c08db99364d0c%7C81a8a8e77115444a865791de036c0d08%7C0%7C0%7C638272230720354966%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=4oWmLQj0c4FQHujcJw1GlCiySwVnjOqeLXRV0f3PVrs%3D&amp;reserved=0">协议</a>。这样的协议有可能成为外交胜利：几十年前的历届美国政府和两党都将以色列和阿拉伯半岛的安全视为至关重要的利益，必要时美国人愿意为之奋斗和牺牲。一项通过以色列和沙特阿拉伯关系正常化来推进这两个目标的协议将会——<em>也应该</em>——受到华盛顿的大张旗鼓和近乎普遍的认可。<br><br>然而，正是因为美国政策制定者将面临庆祝任何已宣布的协议的压力，所以他们需要明确什么是“胜利”，什么不是“胜利”。国会尤其应该准备好就任何协议提出尖锐的问题。一项承诺美国在该地区的存在不减少甚至不断增加的协议，无论是在部队数量还是政策关注方面，都是一个糟糕的协议。除了真正希望与以色列实现关系正常化之外，沙特的任何动机也是如此。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/04/mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-palace-interview/622822/">摘自2022年4月号：绝对权力</a><br><br>一项好的协议是使以色列和海湾国家之间本已升温的关系正式化，同时允许美国——在过去三十年里在该地区花费了不可估量的鲜血和财富——减少在中东的时间和金钱。<br><br>因此，以色列和沙特阿拉伯之间的联姻并不是一场胜利。以色列和埃及之间的和平协议提供了一个警示性的例子。当时，该协议受到欢迎，因为两国在三十年里打了四场灾难性的战争，而该协议在美国对埃及的军事援助的支持下，使这个阿拉伯语世界上人口最多的国家脱离了苏联的轨道。但今天的埃及人民很大程度上憎恨以色列。两国之间几乎没有有意义的社会或经济联系，而目前陷入混乱的政治和金融问题的埃及对以色列持怀疑态度，而不是将其视为合作伙伴。<br><br>以色列和约旦之间的和平也类似。这两种关系取决于美元、安曼和开罗的独裁政权以及受影响国家军事和安全部门之间的合作。两项和平协议都在参与者中培养了一种权利意识：埃及、以色列和约旦政府都认为自己每年欠数十亿美元的军事援助，并对任何可能减少此类援助的建议表示愤怒。埃及的问题尤其严重，该国军队是该国最强大的政治角色，但依赖援助来提供就业机会和保护其经济利益。<br><br>继 2020 年《亚伯拉罕协议》之后，以色列和阿拉伯联合酋长国之间迅速发展的关系，在某种程度上感觉与埃及和约旦的关系有所不同。以色列和阿联酋领导人对中东其他地区的看法彼此相似（而且应该说，通常与华盛顿的看法不同）。例如，穆罕默德·本·扎耶德和他的儿子和兄弟对伊朗和逊尼派伊斯兰主义者构成的威胁与任何以色列人一样感到震惊，而阿联酋雄心勃勃的主权财富基金与以色列初创生态系统之间的协同效应也充满希望。以色列人有理由访问阿布扎比和迪拜，阿联酋人有理由访问海法、耶路撒冷和特拉维夫。每个国家都可以为对方做出贡献——阿联酋的资本、以色列的创新。<br><br>以色列和沙特阿拉伯也应该如此。总体而言，海湾地区是目前世界上为数不多的经济亮点之一。海湾地区的主权财富基金拥有来自石油和天然气收入的大量现金，在国内外大手笔支出，而西方私募股权和风险投资公司则寻求在该地区筹集资金。<br><br>沙特阿拉伯拥有所有富裕的海湾国家中最大的消费者基础，这就是为什么零售商和消费品制造商在那里花费的时间比卡塔尔或阿联酋等国家更多的原因。王储穆罕默德·本·萨勒曼的经济改革使在沙特阿拉伯做生意比过去几年更具吸引力，并且更多的西方公司——当然是在利雅得的压力下——将其区域业务的基础设在沙特阿拉伯，而不是在沙特阿拉伯。阿联酋。<br><br>以色列人可能希望在沙特阿拉伯投资，而沙特人几乎肯定会想在以色列投资。这种对两国关系正常化的激励应该足够了，美国不应该觉得有义务提供更多。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/06/israeli-saudi-relations/395015/">阅读：以色列和沙特阿拉伯——终于在一起了？</a><br><br>尽管如此，有传言称美国计划增加对沙特和以色列安全的承诺，这一前景令我感到担忧。以色列与其邻国之间的和平应该允许美国在该地区部署<em>更少的</em>资源，而不是更多。但美国外交官常常低估他们代表五角大楼做出的承诺。<br><br> 2015 年的伊朗协议就是一个有用的例子。由于一些非常充分的理由，五角大楼被排除在美国和伊朗之间的谈判之外，而较为乐观的政府成员希望这可能会导致美国对该地区政策的新时代。但该协议本身实际上锁定了美国在附近的强大军事态势，以强制伊朗遵守协议：协议签署后，将美军从海湾转移到东亚变得更加困难，而不是更容易。<br><br>我担心，对沙特阿拉伯或以色列做出的任何正式安全承诺都可能会在未来几十年内向中东派遣数万名美军。在冲突中将美军调入海湾比您想象的要困难，因此为了应对突发事件，您需要的大部分物资必须提前部署到该地区。 （在奥巴马政府执政结束时，约有 35,000 名美军半永久驻扎在海湾地区。）美国不应以优先考虑太平洋战区为代价，对中东（昨天的战争现场）做出新的安全承诺。<br><br>不过，我理解耶路撒冷和华盛顿的热情。尽管我担心美国可能会为了完成协议而做出不明智且最终不必要的承诺，但拜登政府——是的，还有之前的特朗普政府——值得高度赞扬。感谢您让我们如此接近对以色列、沙特阿拉伯和美国外交来说将是一项重大成就。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 18:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/us-saudi-israel-normalization-deal/674973/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/us-saudi-israel-normalization-deal/674973/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Hawaii Is a Warning]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>世界不需要更多关于气候变化正在加速的提醒。但我们会继续得到它们。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/6Cu284hcncNsU-91-fOcHAYJrG0=/1x0:999x561/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/ezgif.com_resize/original.gif" alt="夏威夷拉海纳棕榈树移动的 GIF" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>视频由艾德丽安·拉弗朗斯拍摄</figcaption></figure>1886 年 11 月，在檀香山伊奥拉尼宫举行的皇家禧年庆典上，大卫·卡拉卡瓦国王展示了他最近拥有的一件相当引人注目的物品：一个光滑的长方形葫芦，由相思木和寇木制成，包裹着装饰性黄铜，被称为拉阿毛毛风葫芦。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www2.hawaii.edu/~dennisk/texts/introwindgourd.html">传说</a>中，葫芦里蕴含着夏威夷所有的风——只有知道对每个人唱什么歌的人才能召唤出这些风。葫芦本身以夏威夷仁慈的风之女神 La&#39;a Maomao 命名。<br><br>本周早些时候，当我观察到异常猛烈的风吹过考艾岛的棕榈树时，我发现自己想起了葫芦，比我记忆中在夏威夷见过的还要强烈，然后几个小时后，当紧急警报响起时，我又想起了葫芦。出，提醒我注意同样的风在东部约 190 英里的毛伊岛引发的可怕火灾。当疏散令下达时，毛伊岛历史悠久的拉海纳小镇已无希望免遭毁灭。目前官方称至少有 36 人死亡。整个事情发生得快得令人难以理解——快得人们从火焰中跳入大海试图自救。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/climate-change-tipping-points/674778/">阅读：气候崩溃可能会很快发生</a><br><br>当我住在欧胡岛时，在钻石头山脚下的一间小平房里，靠近冲浪胜地 Tonggs，距离如此之近，我可以听到海浪透过卧室的窗户传来，我经常在太平洋海啸预警中心网站打开的情况下入睡。我的手机，像枕头下的护身符一样闪闪发光。我喜欢在昏昏欲睡之前看到网站顶部的绿色横幅<span class="smallcaps">——没有海啸警报、咨询、监视或威胁</span>。但我从未想过要担心岛上发生野火。<br><br> “幸运的是，我们住在夏威夷”是这里的一句俗语，这句话看似甜蜜，但实际上是一种深切的感激之情的表达：对夏威夷人民的善良、对丰富的土地、对美好生活的品质的欣赏。光线，以及这个地方的整体柔和感——铁木的画笔针，挂满成熟芒果的树，冬天的夜空看起来更加紫色。<br><br>和其他地方一样，这里也发生了可怕的事情，而不仅仅是本周火灾的恐怖。当人们称其为“天堂”时，当地人有时会感到愤怒，这是有充分理由的。不止一次，来自东海岸的记者同事得知我是檀香山的记者后，会说<i>“哇，你报道什么？”</i>之类的话。<i>草裙舞和迈泰酒？</i>这样的评论让我意识到那些自以为好奇的人是多么无知。他们本可以发现但从未费心去学习的东西，这让我很生气。<br><br>夏威夷是一个极其复杂的地方，任何热爱夏威夷的人都会告诉你。也许这就是为什么拉海纳突然被烧成平地如此令人惊讶，即使它不应该如此。<br><br>通常，夏威夷让人感觉关系密切，就像每个人都认识每个人一样。发生任何大事之后，感觉就更小了。昨天，我花了大部分时间与岛上的朋友以及夏威夷的各种侨民聊天和发短信，而毛伊岛和大岛仍然在燃烧。一位朋友告诉我，他的一位朋友连夜飞往毛伊岛灭火。另一个人的小儿子和他的祖父母在毛伊岛，每个人都很好，但他们已经 24 小时没有电力或可靠的通讯。另一位朋友，她在拉海纳度过了整个童年，后来搬到了毛伊岛内陆地区，她发短信确认她的<i>家人</i>一切都好，一切都已确定。贯穿所有这些信息的明确主题——除了一遍又一遍地在两个方向上<i>说“谢天谢地，你没事</i>”——是一种明显的措手不及的感觉。我和几个在这里出生和长大的朋友交谈过，没有人记得这样的火灾，甚至没有人记得发生过这样的火灾。夏末的灌木丛火灾时有发生，但总是很容易得到控制。像我一样，没有人记得曾经担心过火灾。<br><br>在夏威夷，孩子们被教导要尊重自然——火山的古老愤怒、海洋的巨大力量和无限回报。每年夏天，飓风都会像发条一样在太平洋上翻滚，但由于物理和偶然的宇宙恩典，它们很少袭击。 （1992 年以 4 级风暴摧毁考艾岛的伊尼基飓风和 1982 年以 1 级风暴袭击考艾岛的飓风伊瓦是证明了这一规则的可怕例外。）一周前，当我看到飓风时多拉仍在积蓄力量，正像一场怪物风暴一样穿过群岛以南数百英里，我默默祈祷道谢，然后很快就忘记了这件事。夏威夷是晴朗的。但就像其他地方一样，它一直是透明的，直到突然之间就变得不透明了。这是夏威夷人们不断互相问的问题：飓风从什么时候开始引发野火？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/07/climate-change-damage-displacement-solastalgia/670614/">阅读：气候变化时代创造了新的情感</a><br><br>加州人讨厌人们被火烧晕。今年夏天早些时候，我是东海岸众多野火新手之一，当时天空变成了橙色，清晨的阳光投下傍晚的阴影，整个城市闻起来像篝火。这只是因为从加拿大飘来的烟雾。尽管如此，这次经历对我来说仍然是一种新的世界末日。 <i>“我们已经这样生活了很多年</i>，”加州人抱怨道。<i>我们告诉过你它也会为你而来。</i>当然，他们是对的。我希望他们没有。<br><br>我们生活在一个充满太多情感、太多表演性反应、太多确定性和太多悲观主义的时代。所有这些互相喊叫的结果是淹没了真正值得关注和关心的事情，更不用说它如何损害了我们团结起来解决生存问题的能力。而且——这是人类韧性和适应性的副产品，这些品质本来对我们很有帮助——有时从理智上理解一种现象是不够的；这与当火焰舔舐自家门时所得到的视角不同。<br><br>群岛上的人们内心深处都知道夏威夷与美国其他地区不同。你可以欺骗自己，认为这会以某种方式保护它免受在该国或世界其他地方遭受苦难的侮辱。 （顺便说一句， <i>La&#39;a Maomao 的</i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wehewehe.org/">字面意思</a>是“神圣的距离” <i>。</i> ）有时这种魔力确实有效。然而，这一次却没有。在不久的将来，某个时候太快了，另一个地方将再次发自内心地感受到我们多年来已经在智力上吸收的知识——我们已经没有时间来保护自己了，当美丽的东西燃烧时，你永远无法真正把它拿回来。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 17:33:46 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hawaii-wildfires-warning-climate-change/674974/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hawaii-wildfires-warning-climate-change/674974/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[An Adorable Way to Study How Kids Get Each Other Sick]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>看哪，雪貂日托中心。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/3WdOumDd5hLtLxj7qea1r1HWZ2U=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/sick_ferrets/original.jpg" alt="嘴里叼着温度计的雪貂" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 《大西洋月刊》的照片插图。资料来源：盖蒂</figcaption></figure>2022 年初，当 Omicron 变种冠状病毒在美国肆虐时，Seema Lakdawala 在匹兹堡敲定了开设一家全新日托中心的计划。她找到了完美的设施并签署了一堆文件；她组装了一堆毛绒玩具、拼图和玩具。这是一个完美的设置，“我多年来一直梦想着”，埃默里大学的病毒学家拉克达瓦拉告诉我。那年春天晚些时候，当她迎来了她的机构的第一批参与者时，她情不自禁地感到自豪：五只年轻的雪貂，其中一只故意感染了流感。<br><br>在接下来的几个月里，拉克达瓦拉和她的同事们观察了几群雪貂在共用的婴儿围栏内嬉戏、摔跤和嬉戏，来回传播乒乓流感病毒。研究人员仔细记录了雪貂的动作；他们记下了每个人接触过的表面和其他动物。他们的早期发现现在正准备在科学期刊上发表，可以帮助研究人员弄清楚流感病毒如何在群体环境中最有效地传播——不仅在雪貂之间，而且在人类儿童之间。<br><br>气溶胶、飞沫、面对面接触、受污染的表面——流感病毒的传播方式有很多。但密歇根大学流行病学家奥布里·戈登表示，流感传播的本质仍然“几乎是一个黑匣子”。尽管经过了数十年的研究，“我们确实不知道每条潜在路线的相对重要性。”不过，现在，婴儿围栏中的雪貂可以帮助研究人员梳理这些动态，甚至有一天，可以为真正的日托设计预防流感的措施。 <br><br><div class="oembed" data-oembed-name="www.youtube.com" data-oembed-src="https://youtu.be/eaNVpYPrMtU"><figure class="c-embedded-video"><div class="embed-wrapper" style="display: block; position:relative; width:100%; height:0; overflow:hidden; padding-bottom:56.21%;"><iframe allow="autoplay; fullscreen; encrypted-media; picture-in-picture;" allowfullscreen="true" class="embedly-embed lazyload" data-src="//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/media.html?src=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2FeaNVpYPrMtU%3Ffeature%3Doembed&amp;display_name=YouTube&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DeaNVpYPrMtU&amp;image=https%3A%2F%2Fi.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2FeaNVpYPrMtU%2Fhqdefault.jpg&amp;key=e59abcd3fdf14abe95641518e479f5c0&amp;type=text%2Fhtml&amp;schema=youtube" frameborder="0" height="480" scrolling="no" style="position:absolute; width:100%; height:100%; top:0; left:0; border:0;" title="YouTube 嵌入" width="854" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></figure></div><figcaption class="caption">雪貂在“日托中心”玩耍，模拟流感病毒在儿童中的传播。由 Seema Lakdawala（埃默里大学）和 Nicole Rockey（杜克大学）提供。</figcaption>领导拉克达瓦拉实验的杜克大学环境工程师妮可·罗基 (Nicole Rockey) 表示，雪貂长期以来一直是“流感感染和传播的黄金标准”。这些动物的呼吸道结构与我们惊人地相似，而且与大多数实验<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8228315/">小鼠</a>不同的是，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6004870/">雪貂</a>很容易感染和传播流感病毒，甚至会出现与许多人类相同的咳嗽、流鼻涕的症状。但大多数针对雪貂的流感传播实验仍然仅限于人工环境：成对的雪貂被关在小笼子里，它们之间有隔板，科学家们在几天甚至几周的时间里盯着它们互相吸入空气。这不是动物在野外相互感染的方式，也不是人类疫情爆发的方式。 “我们 48 小时内不会直接隔着穿孔墙进行互动，”洛基告诉我。<br><br>配备了玩具、空气采样器和摄像机的巨型围栏并不完全是雪貂的<em>自然</em>栖息地。但这种设置确实利用了许多动物顽皮的本能。伦敦大学皇家兽医学院的动物福利研究员爱丽丝·丹瑟（Alice Dancer）表示，雪貂被人类驯化了数千年，“是一种非常顽皮的物种，它们喜欢社交”。这使它们不仅成为流感传播的绝佳模型，而且成为<em>儿童</em>流感传播的绝佳模型，而儿童被认为是流感爆发的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4469206/">主要</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2939723/">驱动因素</a><em>。</em>在日托中心，雪貂们会为玩具争吵、爬上游戏设施、抚摸毛绒蛇。它们互相追逐，被窝起来后就成堆地打盹。他们深情地交换着爱抚、碰碰和小咬。每一次交互都代表一次潜在的传播事件；他们接触的表面以及他们呼吸的共享空气也同样如此。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/04/yamagata-flu-transmission-lineage-extinction/673662/">阅读：流感可能永远不会一样</a><br><br>拉克达瓦拉告诉我，研究人员已经收集了一些结果，“正在稍微改变我对传播的看法。”在一项早期实验中，一只受感染的动物与四只未感染的动物嬉戏，他们惊讶地发现，与流感“捐赠者”直接接触<em>最少的</em>雪貂是房间里唯一生病的“接受者”。拉克达瓦拉告诉我，这似乎有悖常理，直到视频显示，新患病的接受者一直在模仿捐赠者所做的一切——咀嚼它咀嚼的玩具，滚动它滚动的球，刷它刷过的表面。就好像第一只雪貂留下了一串传染性的面包屑，让第二只雪貂去啃食。洛基告诉我，如果这一发现在研究人员现在正在分析的其他实验中得到证实，则可能表明受污染的表面或污染物在病毒传播中发挥的作用超出预期。<br><br>该团队的另一个早期发现也提出了类似的观点。当研究人员加大雪貂日托中心的通风，希望清除空气中的病毒颗粒时，他们发现相同比例的未感染雪貂最终感染了病毒。这令人失望，但考虑到雪貂和孩子们彼此之间以及周围环境的相处方式，这并不完全令人震惊。房间里的空气每三分钟交换一次以上也没关系。每当雪貂跑出房间时，研究人员就会发现玩具、零食站和婴儿围栏的墙壁上涂有病毒颗粒。<br><br>通风并非完全无用：研究小组发现，更多的空气交换似乎确实降低了空气中流感遗传物质的浓度，并且在这种条件下感染的雪貂开始<em>传播</em>病毒的速度较慢——这是一个暗示，拉克达瓦拉认为，他们可能摄入了较低的传染剂量。戈登告诉我，在人类中，这可能会转化为不太严重的疾病病例，尽管这需要得到证实。<br><br>无论洛基和拉克达瓦拉的雪貂发现对人类日托有什么影响，都不一定适用于其他场所。在办公室、医院，甚至是大孩子的学校，人们之间的接触通常要少得多，而且更注重卫生。另外，美国国立卫生研究院福格蒂国际中心的流行病学家塞西尔·维布德说，成年人的身体构造并不像孩子的那样。他们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8014227/">呼吸道</a>更大、更强、更<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8721651/">发达</a>——<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2021830118">一些实验</a>表明，至少对于某些呼吸道病毒来说，年龄越大、体型越大的人，排出的气溶胶就越具有传染性。对于成年人来说，通风可能更为重要。<br><br>拉克达瓦拉和她的同事仍在考虑其他一些可能对雪貂以及最终对孩子更有效的干预措施：加湿器、空气净化器、有针对性的清洁，甚至可能防止人们过于靠近婴儿围栏的一部分。 （他们不打算尝试洗手或戴口罩；想象一下将 N95 绑在雪貂脸上的困难。）拉克达瓦拉还在考虑铜制成的表面（她的团队已经证明铜表面可以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37404191/">在几分钟内使流感病毒失活</a>）是否可以起到保护作用。<br><br>但雪貂围栏中发生的一切仍然会带来警告。 “归根结底，它仍然是一个动物模型，”维布告诉我。尽管雪貂的呼吸道与我们的呼吸道有很多相似之处，但它们的小​​鼻子和口鼻部的形状可能会影响它们咳嗽和打喷嚏的方式。研究人员还没有研究对流感已有免疫力的雪貂之间的传播情况，而一些日托中心的参加者可能会有这种免疫力。与普通（受过如厕训练的）孩子相比，雪貂也更倾向于咬人、摔跤和随心所欲地排便。<br><br>不过，在很大程度上，拉克达瓦拉还是对雪貂的孩子气感到高兴。他们深情又调皮；他们似乎充满活力和欢乐。在发现日托中心的空气采样机器人可以移动后，几只雪貂开始骑着它去兜风。在会议上观看和分享视频时，拉克达瓦拉一遍又一遍地收到一条反馈：<em>哦，是的</em>，父母告诉她。<em>我的孩子们也这样做。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 17:16:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/day-care-ferret-flu-transmission-research/674972/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/day-care-ferret-flu-transmission-research/674972/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Political Rom-Com That Feels Ripped From a Bygone Era]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Prime Video 的<em>《红、白、宝蓝》</em>是一部逃避现实的奇幻作品，无论如何努力都无法完全逃离现实世界。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EMJnjuYnCfFr4SEYAeqpEtcwCoE=/0x0:3000x1688/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/12676351_212db3f560ee45d19a9afc5cf419cc21_master_3000/original.jpg" alt="Prime Video 的《红、白、宝蓝》剧照" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔纳森·普莱姆/亚马逊工作室</figcaption></figure>在 2004 年出现的所有与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/10/12/kerry.concert/index.html">政治</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2004/08/rock-the-vote-goes-im/">相关的</a>流行文化中，最不可思议的巧合之一是两部独立的大制片厂电影的上映，该电影讲述了一位虚构总统的叛逆少女女儿的故事。那年一月， <em>《追逐自由》</em>跟随安娜·福斯特（曼迪·摩尔饰）前往欧洲旅行，在那里她摆脱了父亲的控制，投入了一名卧底特勤局特工的怀抱。同年九月上映的<em>《长女》</em>跟随萨姆·麦肯齐（凯蒂·赫尔姆斯饰）到加利福尼亚大学读第一个学期，在那里她也摆脱了父亲的控制，投入了一名卧底特勤局特工的怀抱。<br><br> 20 世纪 90 年代末和 2000 年代初是这类泡沫浪漫喜剧的繁荣时期，背景设定在现实世界的政治背景下，没有太多现实世界的政治。在<em>《追逐自由》</em> 、 <em>《第一女儿</em>》和 1998 年制作的经典电视剧<em>《我与总统女儿的约会》</em>中，总统的要求主要是作为父亲们对十几岁的女儿加强保护的理由。在有关海外皇室的电影中，例如<em>《公主日记》</em>和<em>《王子与我》</em> ，揭露一个角色是君主制的一部分主要集中在人际影响上。这些电影对政治的乐观态度是其吸引力的一部分。他们感觉自己就像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://collider.com/disney-channel-original-movies-golden-era/">迪士尼频道电影宇宙</a>中的可互换参与者，在这个宇宙中，如果存在政治问题，可以通过某个任性的青少年向他们勤奋的单亲父母敞开心扉来解决——事实证明，他恰好是美国总统。美国。<br><br> <em>《红、白与宝蓝》</em>是一部在 Prime Video 上播放的新电影，其灵感来自于过去充满政治色彩的浪漫喜剧时代，但也有一些值得注意的曲折。影片的主角是美国的长子——一位混血、双性恋的大学生，名叫亚历山大·克莱蒙特-迪亚兹（泰勒·扎克哈·佩雷斯饰），在两人结婚后，他深深地爱上了威尔士的亨利·福克斯-蒙特克里斯汀-温莎王子（尼古拉斯·加利津饰）。被迫假装友谊以维持美国和英国之间的外交关系。作为一部奇怪的情侣浪漫喜剧，它是认真且易于观看的模因素材，即兴发挥了经典的敌人到恋人的比喻。与它的一些前辈不同的是，它试图将其爱情故事有意义地置于当代政治的高风险舞台上。但它的欢快幻想——年轻人的滑稽动作在成人的负责任治理背景下上演——感觉越来越虚假，而且在当前地缘政治动荡的时刻，落地有些令人不安。<br><br> <em>《红、白与宝蓝》</em>由马修·洛佩兹执导，并与泰德·马拉维尔共同撰写剧本，改编自作家凯西·麦克奎斯顿 2019 年的小说。该书出版后，迅速在社交媒体和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/02/sex-intimacy-love-scenes-tv-movies-humanity-expression/673140/">热衷浪漫、</a>畅销书<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/red-white-royal-blue-book-summer-beach-read-11565285001">的病毒式传播机器 BookTok</a>上赢得了粉丝。不难看出这本书赢得读者的原因：麦克奎斯顿在 2016 年总统选举期间开始写这本小说，当时女性领导国家的想法似乎触手可及。在唐纳德·特朗普当选的震惊之后，麦克奎斯顿的书——以另一条时间线为背景，2016 年一名女性确实<em>获胜</em>——成为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/unthinking-pleasure-on-casey-mcquistons-red-white-royal-blue/">读者逃避现实的刺激</a>，尤其是那些像作者一样的酷儿读者。在<em>红、白、宝蓝</em>的颠倒世界里，同性性行为大量存在，恐同症受到广泛谴责。亚历克斯不仅仅是一个普通的孩子，他的妈妈支持他作为一个年轻的酷儿；他是德克萨斯州一位民主党人的儿子，她公开拥抱她的孩子，帮助她将家乡变成蓝色，从而赢得连任。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2022/02/can-rom-coms-make-a-comeback/622868/">阅读：美国需要浪漫喜剧的救助</a><br><br>在他们贪婪而令人陶醉的求爱过程中，亚历克斯和亨利互相教导对方有关大西洋两岸的生活；如果这是一部由阿彻韦尔、哈里王子和梅根·马克尔的制作公司批准的当代酷儿爱情故事，<em>汉密尔顿</em>可能会这么想。 “在美国，如果你是一个姓氏中带有 Z 的移民，那么没有多少位高权重的人看起来像你或听起来像你，”一天早上亚历克斯在床上告诉亨利。 “我有机会成为我父亲在成长过程中看不到的人。”乌玛·瑟曼 (Uma Thurman) 饰演艾伦·克莱蒙特 (Ellen Claremont) 总统，她是 2016 年许多美国人投票支持的精益领导力的明显替身：她是一位多才多艺、自信的职业女性，27 岁时首次当选政治职务，并在连任竞选期间从她多元化的员工那里得到了线索。我们被引导相信，选举地图具有竞争性，但这并不公平。来自德克萨斯州的白人女性不仅可以赢得两次总统选举，而且还可以与她的墨西哥裔美国丈夫和他们的混血儿孩子一起赢得总统选举。<br><br>尽管如此，在后特朗普时代、后 1 月 6 日世界中<em>，《红、白和宝蓝》</em>还是忍不住要直面这种叙事方式的局限性。这部电影进入了一种政治氛围，两党执政不再是稳定的选举制度，国家政客公开主张对竞争对手使用暴力。麦克奎斯顿的书将克莱蒙特总统的对手描绘成极右翼共和党人，而这部电影则将他描绘成一位中间派保守派、一位不威严的密歇根州州长，其主要竞选纲领是为中西部带来更多就业机会。现代共和党政客的名册要可怕得多：在特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/">不断受到起诉的</a>背景下，共和党在德克萨斯州等州推动<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/texass-immigration-policy-biden/674784/">惩罚性移民政策，</a>佛罗里达州州长罗恩·德桑蒂斯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/viktor-orban-illiberalism-ron-desantis-universities/674915/">在全国范围内的声望上升</a>，目睹了充满希望的<em>西翼</em>风格屏幕上的选举感觉很不和谐。<br><br>亨利是第四顺位继承人，甚至在接受同性恋身份之前就对自己的地位感到幻灭。但几年来，媒体对现实生活中的苏塞克斯公爵和公爵夫人的报道和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/giselleruhiyyih/status/1607096923441217536?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1607096923441217536%7Ctwgr%5E370af970e88acb999604b55921d0274bffb127ec%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dexerto.com%2Ftv-movies%2Fthe-invitation-on-netflix-compared-to-harry-meghan-fan-fiction-vampires-2019163%2F">粉丝小说</a>不断疯狂，人们很难不对亨利表面上顿悟的时刻翻白眼。 “皇室的观念在 21 世纪已经过时了，”他有一次说道。 “有时我想知道我们所做的事情是否对人们的生活产生任何有意义的影响。”这并不完全是一个标题中带有“温莎”字样的人的真诚反思，温莎是一个真实的王室，具有丰富的现实世界背景，而当这部电影对一个机构提出如此温和的批评时，它就处于最软弱的状态。尽管如此，似乎还是希望观众能够尊重并为之着迷。<br><br>这部电影真正成功的地方在于捕捉到了年轻人迷恋的独特老套动力，扎克哈·佩雷斯和加利津为他们的角色带来了一种为粉丝打造的温暖，加深了电影对他们关系有时摇摇欲坠的描写。大多数情况下，不情愿的年轻情人即使是白痴，对彼此或对周围的世界也是迷人的：他们在手机中输入“HRH [殿下]迪克黑德王子💩”之类的联系人姓名，进行交易分享对个人意义重大的珠宝首饰，并睁大眼睛、敞开心扉，互相讲述童年的快乐。这些场景总体上令人愉快， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2022/film/news/nicholas-galitzine-anne-hathaway-the-idea-of-you-1235375884/">特别是在加利津的例子中</a>，它们为我们至少对另一部<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://screenrant.com/booktok-sensaions-currently-adapted-to-screen/">即将出版的 BookTok 改编作品</a>的预期提供了谨慎乐观的看法。 （他将与安妮·海瑟薇一起主演<em>《The Idea of​​ You</em> 》，该片改编自罗宾·李 2017 年的小说<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vogue.com/article/idea-of-you-book">，灵感来自哈利·斯泰尔斯</a>。）<br><br>当演员体现出他的角色中比较轻松的怪癖时，他会表现出一些青春期的活力，这使得那些千禧年时代的政治浪漫喜剧看起来很有趣。那些早期电影中的年轻人的恶作剧不再与政府里有能力、头脑冷静的成年人的行为形成鲜明对比，这不是他的错<em>，也不是《红、白、宝蓝》</em>的错。这是一个不同的世界，一些古老的故事已经不再流传。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 16:00:22 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/red-white-and-royal-blue-movie-review/674971/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/red-white-and-royal-blue-movie-review/674971/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Scandal Pushing Peers Into the Abyss]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>看似无害的盛会的荣誉制度隐藏着一定程度的唯利是图和任人唯亲，这是任何有自尊的民主国家都不能容忍的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/CjMtSj8MkTUYPVtid8RqxTR2Z0s=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/peer_influence/original.jpg" alt="一张英国上议院议员坐在英国上议院议事厅的照片，其中一些还戴着假发" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>蒂姆·格雷厄姆照片库/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>一直困扰自由派英国人<span class="smallcaps">的一件事</span>是，美国人可能认为<i>《唐顿庄园》</i>这样的电视剧是半纪录片，而英国仍然是一个阶级森严的社会，受制于继承等级和社会地位的观念。因为自由派英国人知道这是不公平和不真实的。或者更确切地说，这是不公平和不真实的，除了一个特殊的例外：英国的荣誉制度，即向公民授予奖章和头衔的惯例。<br><br>这种古老特权的例外给英国政府及其新任首相里希·苏纳克带来了一个痛苦的夏天。这是一个既有趣又有点羞耻的传奇故事。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">几乎所有国家</span>都有荣誉制度——公共美德本身很少是奖励。每年，约有 2,000 名英国人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wearebayleaf.com/kings-honours-statistics/">获得</a>某种程度的荣誉（意大利和法国获得的荣誉更多）。与我们发明的一些传统一样，英国的荣誉制度只能追溯到 20 世纪初。在这个动荡的时期——当有组织的劳工在游行时，爱尔兰人想要地方自治，而妇女参政论者正在打破窗户——统治阶级在寻找将人民与国家结合起来的方法方面必然是最足智多谋的。<br><br>因此，大英帝国勋章于 1917 年设立，作为奖励在一战期间做出非战斗服务的国王臣民的一种方式。撇开帝国协会不谈，这个奖项是无害的。所有获奖者都会兴奋地前往皇宫接受君主或王室成员颁发的勋章。然后，他们就可以在正式地址中使用这个头衔，从而获得威望。本来已经订满的餐厅里突然为领主和骑士找到了座位。获奖者会见皇室成员的照片出现在书房的墙上，每个受到祝福的人都会有一个故事，讲述已故女王如何对他们微笑，或者查尔斯如何嘲笑他们的笑话。众所周知，叛逆的演员一夜之间就变成了保皇党。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1863/08/an-american-in-the-house-of-lords/627956/">摘自 1863 年 8 月号：上议院的美国人</a><br><br>荣誉制度的这一部分令人惊讶地民主——或者至少不亚于属于扶轮社。任何人都可以提名某人，甚至是他们自己。公务员收集提名，进行分类筛选，然后将其缩减为最终名单，提交给来自公共生活相关领域的伟人和善人委员会：科学技术、文化艺术、慈善部门等在。毫无疑问，审查是彻底和真诚的，但在英国，有时会听到一定程度的可能是嫉妒的愤世嫉俗——关于大英帝国勋章（OBE），因为其他虫子的努力而被授予。<br><br>我最近遇到了一位上议院女议员，有人突然给她发了一封申请荣誉的电子邮件。他们问她是否可以提供参考。 “但我从来没有听说过你，”她反对道。 “哦，没关系，”电子邮件发件人回答道。 “我带你去吃午饭，我们可以互相认识一下。”<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">OBE 并不是</span>荣誉制度中造成麻烦的一方。甚至更有声望的骑士爵位也不是。被封为爵士可能不会被认为是民主国家展示其社会包容性和多元文化价值观的自然方式，但在过去的几年里，我的两个朋友被封为爵士：一个是黑人，另一个是同性恋。两人自然都表示有点尴尬，但这被他们年长的亲戚获得该奖项时的喜悦所抵消。<br><br>问题出在贵族身上。成为“贵族”并成为上议院议员，同时就意味着获得荣誉并被任命为英国立法机构成员。贵族或女士不仅可以预订最好的餐厅，而且还坐在威斯敏斯特宫并拥有很大程度的政治影响力，上议院是民选下议院的第二议院。就像众议院和参议院组成美国国会一样，英国的两院组成议会，其重要区别在于，与上议院不同，美国参议院是民选机构。尽管立法的主动权属于下议院，但上议院仍然通过辩论、修改和批准立法提案来发挥影响力。<br><br>一旦登上上议院议事厅的皮革软垫长凳，您就可以加入托尼·布莱尔时代未完成的改革留下的 90 名左右世袭贵族（公爵、侯爵、伯爵、子爵）以及两打主教的行列。英国国教，包括坎特伯雷大主教。贵族爵位很少被世袭。距离前三年已经过去了近40年。但终身贵族（他们的头衔不可继承）一直都是存在的——无论谁提名上议院议员，都可以行使相当大的赞助权力。同行，例如美国最高法院的成员，是终身任职的。<br><br>封爵通常每年举行两次，一次是新年授勋名单，另一次是君主生日授勋名单。实际上，当今的首相会提出一系列他或她想要封爵的人，按照惯例，其中包括一些来自反对党的提名人以及一些由公务员部门提出的其他人。然后，独立委员会将检查这些被提名者的健康状况。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/08/britain-lords-canada-senate-scandal/402125/">阅读：两个立法院的故事</a><br><br>然而，除此之外，还有另一个紧随大选之后的名单：所谓的解散名单，其中包括即将从下议院退休的政客，可能还有一些剩余的用处。最后，也是最有害的，是授予即将卸任总理的名单。这简直就是一种奖励老同志和亲密亲信的方式。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">输入——或者更确切地说，退出</span>——鲍里斯·约翰逊。甚至在去年夏天辞去首相职务之前，约翰逊就利用荣誉名单将明显不适合的人提拔为上议院议员，从而制造了典型的混乱。 2020年，他不顾军情五处安全部门的建议，颇具争议地将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/13/world/europe/uk-oligarchs-russia-ukraine.html">俄罗斯寡头、前克格勃官员</a>的报纸老板之子叶夫根尼·列别杰夫提升为贵族。一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-60792115">批评人士</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnsons-russian-crony-evgeny-lebedev-got-peerage-after-spies-dropped-warning-3dp6sw29x">怀疑</a>，列别杰夫在约翰逊担任伦敦市长期间对他的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/jul/16/carole-cadwalladr-boris-johnson-lebedevs-prime-ministers-defining-scandal">支持</a>，以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/26/boris-johnson-security-evgeny-lebedev-perugia-party">据报道</a>约翰逊访问列别杰夫豪华翁布里亚宅邸期间的盛情款待，是导致这一决定的因素。<br><br>并非所有离任总理都会提交荣誉名单。布莱尔没有；戈登·布朗也没有。然而，约翰逊提出了至少<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/jun/11/boris-johnson-peerages-honours-list-row">16 人的名字来成为同侪</a>。其中一些是年轻的、资质不足的前助手；一些人卷入了大流行封锁期间的“派对门”丑闻，这是公众对约翰逊失去信心的主要原因；其中四人是现任保守党议员，忠于约翰逊。<br><br>除了任人唯亲的表象外，最后一类议员面临的直接问题是一个直接的政治问题：为了获得贵族头衔，这些议员将不得不辞去下议院席位，引发苏纳克政府的特别选举，以处理上任后留下的烂摊子。约翰逊和他的继任者利兹·特拉斯可能很容易失败。<br><br>纳丁·多里斯（Nadine Dorries）就是其中一位议员。多里斯是一位来自工人阶级家庭、好斗的利物浦人，也是一位不寻常的保守党人。多里斯在党内主流中属于右翼，自 2005 年首次当选以来，长达 14 年的时间里，她都没有被提名担任政府职务。直到 2019 年，她才被约翰逊任命为初级卫生部长，她曾在 2019 年大选中支持约翰逊。当年党的领导。此前，她因参加以澳大利亚丛林为背景的电视真人秀节目而闻名，在那里她被迫吃掉骆驼的脚趾和鸵鸟的肛门。她成功地将这位名人融入到一系列以 20 世纪 50 年代利物浦为背景的粗俗小说中。约翰逊下台时，多里斯已获得内阁文化部长职位。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/07/boris-johnson-profile/594379/">阅读：鲍里斯·约翰逊遇见了他的命运</a><br><br>去年七月，当约翰逊的高级内阁同事（包括苏纳克）通过<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9702785/#:~:text=In%20July%202022%2C%20an%20unprecedented,the%20second%20minister%20to%20resign.">辞职</a>抛弃他们的领导人并使他的职位难以维持时，多里斯立场坚定。对一些人来说，她对老板的辩护几乎是一种浪漫的忠诚，但他的党内只有他认识到她的能力并奖励了她，而他那些势利的前任却没有这样做。<br><br>因此，约翰逊提名多里斯为贵族。但当最终名单公布时，她的名字却没有出现在上面。 “我出生在贫困中，然后自己摆脱了贫困......然后在公共服务中找到了一个角色，”深感失望的多里斯在<i>《每日邮报》</i>上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-12187013/NADINE-DORRIES-sinister-forces-stopped-girl-reaching-House-Lords.html">写道</a>。 “在上议院占有一席之地就是对这一点的认可。”相反，她继续说道，“邪恶势力密谋反对我，让我心碎。”<br><br>多里斯没有透露她可能的迫害者的名字，但即将离任的总理荣誉名单的控制权最终掌握在新任总理手中。因此，目前她仍继续担任国会议员，尽管她可能只是在等待时机，因为她的辞职和另一次特别选举将给苏纳克带来极大的不便。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">多丽丝事件</span>有一种娱乐性的真人秀氛围，但约翰逊名单上令人遗憾的事情却让人们重新审视已经声名狼藉的贵族制度。随着<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/truss-pm-honours-list-one-gong-for-every-four-days-in-no-10-902jx9zqz">本周特拉斯离职名单的消息</a>，这种制度危机感进一步加剧：据报道，她的四位上议院提名人中，一位是她担任首相 49 天的副幕僚长，另一位是她的副幕僚长。一位<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/think-tanks-institute-economic-affairs-liz-truss-economy-crash/">智囊团盟友，支持</a>决定了她命运的灾难性经济计划。<br><br>早在 2021 年， <i>《星期日泰晤士报》</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/new-tory-sleaze-row-as-donors-who-pay-3m-get-seats-in-house-of-lords-2575s6jmp">就报道称</a>，“在过去的二十年里，该党的所有 16 位主要财务主管……都获得了上议院的席位。”一位匿名消息人士甚至告诉该报，一位捐赠者“被诱惑向该党捐赠了 100 万英镑”，因为这将带来贵族爵位。根据<i>《卫报》</i> 2022 年的估计，近十分之一的保守党同僚向该党捐赠了超过 10 万英镑（127,000 美元）。<br><br>一位冷漠的宪政历史学家几年前写道，利用贵族爵位进行庇护可能是帮助首相实现目标的有用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmselect/cmpubadm/212/21206.htm">“润滑剂”</a> 。但这种不受约束的做法的后果之一就是第二议院的成员数量不断膨胀。事实上，我们必须感谢缺席的人：如果779名成员同时到场，就<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/feb/06/who-needs-house-of-lords-meet-peers-rattling-the-commons">没有位置</a>了。<br><br>第二个更严重的后果是公众对上议院改革的支持不断增加，包括<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/labours-plan-to-abolish-the-house-of-lords-what-exactly-has-been-proposed-and-the-chances-keir-starmer-will-adopt-it-195976">要求废除上议院改革</a>。在布莱尔政府失败的地方，今天的反对党工党领袖<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/nov/19/keir-starmer-i-will-abolish-house-of-lords-to-restore-trust-in-politics#:~:text=Starmer%20had%20pledged%20to%20abolish,elements%20of%20his%20leadership%20pitch.">提议承担改革事业</a>。但凯尔·斯塔默爵士 (Sir Keir Starmer) 的任务极其艰巨，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://labour.org.uk/people/keir-starmer/">于 2014 年</a>因担任政府检察机关负责人而被封为爵士。这种宪法改革将消耗大量的政治资本、时间和精力，但很难保证普通选民会奖励这种努力。<br><br>这就产生了一个不可能的难题：民意调查<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-12308975/Most-voters-want-House-Lords-abolished-survey-finds.html">显示</a>，英国人对一个腐蚀他们信任的制度几乎没有信心，但他们不太可能感谢政治领导人解决这个问题。上议院的高级成员担心该机构的声誉，并且一段时间以来一直<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmpubadm/662/662.pdf">主张</a>缩小其规模并减少对政治赞助的影响。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">不久前</span>，我受邀参加上议院为一位老朋友举办的聚会，他被授予一项重大荣誉——为了保护这个人的隐私，我们称之为卧室勋章（荣誉制度为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.royal.uk/the-order-of-the-garter">陌生人提供古董）</a>事实上，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.royal.uk/the-order-of-the-garter">标题</a>远不止于此）。我确实钦佩这个人的成就，但我是在一个共产主义家庭长大的，所以，在这个活动上，我感觉有点像贵格会会议上的理查德·道金斯：爱人们，但想知道他们是否偷偷地抢夺了饮料内阁。<br><br>威斯敏斯特宫的房间天花板很高，墙壁上挂满了 18 世纪海战的大型画作，直棂窗户俯瞰着泰晤士河。物质环境是对帝国荣耀的怀旧之情与现代世界不合时宜的氛围的完美体现。我向我认识的一位勤奋的工党男爵夫人谈到了这一点。 “这就是为什么他们中的许多人想进入上议院，”她说。 “搬出这里，一半人都会放弃爵位。”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2010/10/almost-noble/308211/">克里斯托弗·希钦斯：近乎高贵</a><br><br>将立法机关迁出威斯敏斯特宫——这座宫殿实际上已经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.eu/article/palace-westminster-falling-down-british-democracy-house-chamber-lords/">摇摇欲坠</a>，屋顶和管道严重漏水，砖石倒塌——是任何一个不那么墨守成规的政体都会做的事情。国会议员和同僚不会考虑这一点，而是花费数十亿英镑来支撑这座建筑。当然，它应该变成博物馆。<br><br>如果这听起来有点反传统，部分原因是，尽管我从未获得过一项荣誉，但我是相当多的英国人中无论如何也不会接受这一荣誉的人之一。如果我接受“锣”，我已故的母亲非但不会感到高兴，反而会在她的可生物降解的棺材里旋转。在拒绝一项荣誉时，我会加入拉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bl.uk/people/rudyard-kipling#:~:text=Kipling's%20reputation%20was%20at%20its,Prize%20for%20Literature%20in%201907.">迪亚德·吉卜林</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/T-E-Lawrence">TE·劳伦斯</a>、<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bl.uk/people/virginia-woolf">弗吉尼亚·伍尔夫</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/20/arts/20iht-20cndscofield.11293158.html">保罗·斯科菲尔德</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/obe-celebrities-rejected-queens-honours-b2270641.html">大卫·鲍伊</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/obe-celebrities-rejected-queens-honours-b2270641.html">奈杰拉·劳森</a>等令人惊讶的拒绝者行列。<br><br>其他人则拒绝接受荣誉，或者在某些情况下，由于与帝国主义有联系而戏剧性地归还荣誉。但大英帝国勋章可能很快就会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2021/jun/11/new-calls-to-replace-empire-with-excellence-in-uk-honours-system">更名</a>。将会有一场关于它的文化战争，但英国不能继续以一个不再存在的政治实体命名的奖项，它只能提醒人们征服其他民族的不光彩历史。但即使是对荣誉制度进行有限的改革，也需要考虑英国人民的愿望——包括那些不是像约翰逊这样的老伊顿公学学生，但像多丽丝一样必须努力奋斗的人——住在大房子的楼上，俯视楼下。在其他人身上。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/britain-honors-system-peerage-lords/674963/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/britain-honors-system-peerage-lords/674963/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Aristotle’s 10 Rules for a Good Life]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>古希腊的幸福秘诀<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/doEL_VA5lhk_sr1Gl-bTM9fgU64=/0x0:3000x1688/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/HowToBuildALife149/original.jpg" alt="一个男人的插图，他的 10 个指尖上每个都代表着一件好事" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>扬·布奇克 (Jan Buchczik) 插图</figcaption></figure><i data-stringify-type="italic">想了解亚瑟的最新写作吗？ <a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/how-to-build-a-life/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/how-to-build-a-life/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">注册后</a>，每次有新专栏出现时都会收到一封电子邮件。</i><br><br><span class="smallcaps">许多人都说</span>他们正在寻找幸福。他们花费大量时间和资源寻找幸福的秘密，就像老式矿工寻找黄金一样。但对于历史上的一些圣人来说，这是错误的做法。幸福不是可以<i>找到的东西；而是可以找到的</i>东西。这是<i>吸引人</i>的东西。<br><br>也许第二条道路最著名的支持者是希腊哲学家亚里士多德。他将幸福定义为<i>“eudaemonia</i> ”，意思是“良好的精神”。对于我们现代人来说，这可能听起来很虚幻，就像很多人（在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/11/finding-happiness-and-meaning-in-politically-divided-america/672130/">我看来</a>是错误的）追逐的肤浅的快乐感觉一样。相反，这位哲学家的意思是，幸福是一种神圣的状态，它会随心所欲地降临到我们每个人身上。我们唯一的责任就是打开它的大门。我们通过美好生活来做到这一点。<br><br>为了生活得好，我们应该实践特定的美德，并使它们成为习惯。正如亚里士多德在他的<i>《尼各马可伦理学》</i>中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0054%3Abook%3D1%3Achapter%3D9">所写</a>，“如果通过自己的努力获得幸福比通过财富的恩赐更好，那么我们就有理由认为这就是赢得幸福的方式。”以下是他推荐的 10 条美德——正如现代研究表明的那样，这些美德通常确实能吸引善良的人。<br><br><em>想听 Arthur C. Brooks 的更多信息吗？ Join him and a selection of today&#39;s best writers and boldest voices at The Atlantic Festival on September 28 and 29. Get your pass <a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/live/atlantic-festival-2023/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/live/atlantic-festival-2023/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">here</a> .</em><br><br> <b>1.</b><b> </b><b>Courage</b><br> Aristotle <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0054%3Abook%3D3%3Achapter%3D6">wrote</a> about courage in the context of the willingness to sacrifice one&#39;s life, such as in war. Whether he would recognize the virtue in our modern settings is hard to guess—who knows what he would say about the fear of being canceled on social media? But the question at hand is not the source of fear but whether courage—to act in the face of fear rather than give in to it—invites happiness. And the research suggests that it does: Scholars have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259778922_Biological_contributions_to_well-being_The_relationships_amongst_temperament_character_strengths_and_resilience">shown</a> that courage can lead to resilience after adversity, and resilience <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://psycnet.apa.org/record/2009-07991-007">leads</a> to greater happiness.<br><br> <b>2.</b><b> </b><b>Temperance</b><br> By this, the philosopher means self-control in the face of one&#39;s appetites and base impulses. He would classify the hippie motto “If it feels good, do it!” as a recipe for misery. Modern researchers investigating self-control agree, but with a twist. Scholars writing in the <i>Journal of Personality</i> in 2017 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/jopy.12322?casa_token=xFX0iDLDuiQAAAAA%3AfPL8aHFxVyoSerYzXI9M4aTRzOK-q_SMOPXPgMgGf9gzupRILN3uZvR-ZMakYB2hPOk1F9PnepszUL0">found</a> that as impulse control among college students increased over the course of a day, positive affect initially <i>fell</i> . As self-control kept rising, however, negative feelings decreased; happiness rose to its highest levels when self-control was at its highest as well. In other words, a little moderation isn&#39;t so good for well-being, but immoderate moderation may be great.<br><br> <b>3.</b><b> </b><b>Liberality</b><br> By this, the philosopher is referring not to politics (liberal <i>ism</i> ) but to money. Specifically, he recommends avoiding stinginess but without being profligate. In fact, evidence suggests that being a cheapskate influences your well-being. For example, three economists in 2014 set up an ultimatum-bargaining game in which participants had to split a certain amount of money: One participant offered a certain split; the other could say yes or no, but <i>no</i> meant that neither side got anything, so the offer of a lousy split could be answered with spite. The authors <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0108218">found</a> that physical stress levels were higher for both parties when the bargaining involved offered a split lower than 40 percent.<br><br> <b>4.</b><b> </b><b>Magnificence</b><br> Related to liberality is what Aristotle <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.loebclassics.com/view/aristotle-nicomachean_ethics/1926/pb_LCL073.207.xml">calls</a> “magnificence,” according to which a person “will think how he can carry out his project most nobly and splendidly, rather than how much it will cost and how it can be done most cheaply.” He was not asserting here that the path to happiness is to buy an ostentatious yacht; rather, magnificence <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://philarchive.org/archive/ATHADO">means</a> giving to projects that benefit a large number of people. Today, we might call this “munificence”—to be as philanthropic as you reasonably can be. For this, the support is unambiguous: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.journalppw.com/index.php/jpsp/article/view/4535">Giving feels good</a> .<br><br> <b>5.</b><b> </b><b>Greatness of soul</b><br> A great-souled person, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/ergo/12405314.0002.002/--modern-greatness-of-soul-in-hume-and-smith?rgn=main;view=fulltext">according</a> to Aristotle, acts like his close predecessor in ancient Greek philosophy, Socrates, who was a “being indifferent to good and bad fortune.” This requires being high-minded—not that you can&#39;t tell the difference between pleasant and unpleasant things, but that you are occupied by what is deeper and more meaningful in life than transitory pleasures and passing irritations. Indeed, research comparing the pursuit of pleasure versus of meaning among adolescents <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Linting-Zhang/publication/364186853_Pursuing_Pleasure_or_Meaning_A_Cross-Lagged_Analysis_of_Happiness_Motives_and_Well-being_in_Adolescents/links/6353a4656e0d367d91b4a52e/Pursuing-Pleasure-or-Meaning-A-Cross-Lagged-Analysis-of-Happiness-Motives-and-Well-being-in-Adolescents.pdf?_sg%5B0%5D=started_experiment_milestone&amp;_sg%5B1%5D=started_experiment_milestone&amp;origin=journalDetail&amp;_rtd=e30%3D">shows</a> that the latter leads to greater happiness. In other words, get off social media and read, say, <i>Nicomachean Ethics</i> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/03/covid-vaccine-hesitancy-anti-vaxxer-history/673522/">Read: To understand anti-vaxxers, consider Aristotle</a><br><br> <b>6.</b><b> </b><b>Gentleness</b><br> The virtue of gentleness refers to a propensity toward kindness and an ability to control your temper. The idea is that to be self-possessed in this way brings happiness. If true, then gentleness&#39;s opposite, aggression, should lower well-being by making it harder to manage one&#39;s own emotions. Researchers have tested this idea by asking people to think of someone they despise, and then either to imagine violent, malicious actions toward the person or to focus on a neutral thought (specifically, what they planned to do the following Wednesday—presumably <i>not</i> beat up the person in question). They <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0886260518812796?journalCode=jiva">found</a> that the aggressive thinkers began to brood over their fantasy assault and experienced lower well-being than the temperate crew as a result.<br><br> <b>7.</b><b> </b><b>Truthfulness about yourself</b><br> Aristotle put a great premium on honesty. He counseled against “pretense in the form of exaggeration” and boastfulness, but also against self-deprecation. You might say he recommended that we seek something like secure humility, through which we recognize ourselves and can show others who we are without either puffery or self-denigration. This tracks with the general work on humility, which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Lisa-Ross-4/publication/357425333_Humility_Personality_and_Psychological_Functioning/links/6238bf09781d2e6df7ab6792/Humility-Personality-and-Psychological-Functioning.pdf">correlates</a> with lower levels of neuroticism and depression, as well as with a greater love of life. But it is also consistent with research <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/17439760801999461">showing</a> that insecurity and excessive self-criticism are associated with anxiety and sadness.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2014/09/when-philosophy-becomes-therapy/380531/">Read: When philosophy becomes therapy</a><br><br> <b>8.</b><b> </b><b>公平</b><br>This is a word that gets a lot of attention in our modern debates. It commonly involves efforts to increase fairness and to redress past discrimination. And it is manifestly true that when people believe they are being treated unfairly, it <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/0956797611417262">lowers their happiness</a> . But Aristotle meant something totally different. “The equitable man,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0054%3Abook%3D5%3Achapter%3D10">wrote</a> the philosopher, “is one who by choice and habit … does not stand on his rights unduly, but is content to receive a smaller share although he has the law on his side.” He called this “a special kind of Justice.” For this proposition, I can find no specific empirical evidence. However, it is almost certainly related to the next virtue.<br><br> <b>9.</b><b> </b><b>饶恕</b><br>Aristotle. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0054%3Abook%3D6%3Achapter%3D11">wrote</a> about the virtue of consideration for others. To the contemporary ear, this sounds like politeness, or sensitivity to others&#39; feelings, but the philosopher was recommending something much trickier: forgiveness and forbearance toward others&#39; faults. The wisdom of this advice has a large modern literature to support it. Virtually every study of forgiveness <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://osf.io/8qzgw/">shows</a> that practicing it purposefully and letting go of grievances lowers depression and anxiety symptoms.<br><br> <b>10.</b><b> </b><b>Modesty</b><br> Modesty is often thought in the modern world to resemble humility. But Aristotle defined it as refraining from shameful (if tempting) behavior—and applied this even to private conduct. This conception of modesty makes it similar to temperance, except that instead of moderation in the face of base appetites, we should abstain completely from vices. He added a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0054:book=4:chapter=9&amp;highlight=modesty">caveat</a> , however: Modesty could be a virtue only if “a good man would be ashamed if he were to do so and so.” In other words, you have to believe a certain action is vicious in order to be virtuous in avoiding it. I personally have no moral qualms about liquor but don&#39;t drink myself, so by the Aristotelian standard, my teetotaling is not a virtue. Bearing this caveat in mind, this kind of modesty is indeed a happiness strategy: When people undertake what they consider <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/abs/10.1126/science.1251560?casa_token=RE8pgoNigLIAAAAA:TcdOOZGDpCbkQbmv_wZgSuAGB-YrCj_FrXPAg7kR4I0-p9wP-Bn3iBHGcMVa1TMHqJvHiauz-0vU">moral acts</a> , they gain in happiness and even more so in sense of purpose; when they commit immoral acts, they experience the opposite.<br><br> A <span class="smallcaps">ristotle proposed these</span> happiness virtues more than two millennia ago, but I believe they provide a handy checklist today for living well. Here&#39;s an abbreviated list you might just want to put up on your fridge, or tape to the bottom of your computer screen.<br><br> 1. Name your fears and face them.<br> 2. Know your appetites and control them.<br> 3. Be neither a cheapskate nor a spendthrift.<br> 4. Give as generously as you can.<br> 5. Focus more on the transcendent; disregard the trivial.<br> 6. True strength is a controlled temper.<br> 7. Never lie, especially to yourself.<br> 8. Stop struggling for your fair share.<br> 9. Forgive others, and forbear their weaknesses.<br> 10. Define your morality; live up to it, even in private.<br><br> None of these rules is easy to follow. It is harder still to make them into habits. But the payoff—a well-earned visit from sweet <i>eudaemonia</i> —is worth the effort.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/aristotle-10-rules-happy-life/674905/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/aristotle-10-rules-happy-life/674905/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Owls Are Not What They Seem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The birds possess even uncannier powers than we&#39;ve imagined. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/cf-jFaxryUEJOGIUZCoPGyTKLTs=/0x163:2321x3065/648x810/media/img/2023/08/01/CC_Giggs_Owls/original.jpg" alt="白色背景上站立角猫头鹰的深色墨迹状插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Rop Van Mierlo</figcaption></figure> <span class="smallcaps">In the moments</span> before seeing an owl comes a feeling like intuition.我不会忘记有一天晚上，当我站在悉尼郊区的阳台上时，周围丛林中每一个清醒的生物都突然冻结了。就连青蛙似乎也想放弃它们吵闹的身体。<i>谁去那里？</i>几秒钟后，一只强大的猫头鹰（澳大利亚本土物种的名称）落在栏杆上，我也差点从皮肤上跳下来。猫头鹰有梗犬那么大，但像刚放了一天的聚酯薄膜气球一样懒洋洋地漂浮着，在我耳中听着很安静。在针落的寂静中，它沿着栏杆弹跳。我从未听说过它的爪子接触到金属。我知道，猫头鹰本身的听力非常敏锐，它能听出负鼠皮毛下心脏的跳动。看不见的，第二只猫头鹰——我猜是第一只猫头鹰的伴侣——发出了低沉的木管叫声。<br><br>猫头鹰的叫声通常看起来像幽灵或未成熟的声音。双重魔法：猫头鹰可以让我们怀疑自己的能力，同时让我们对它们的奥秘感到好奇。 Of some 260 owl species at large in the night, at dusk, and less commonly during daylight, many are stealthily camouflaged and decked out with decibel-dampening feathers, their shrieks floating without clear origin. The young of some of those species have long been practicing. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/27/nyregion/lord-of-the-winter.html">Great horned owls</a> find their voice while they are still doubled over in the dark of their moon-shaped egg. Having punctured the small air cell inside the egg&#39;s membrane with their budding beak, the proto-owlets inflate their lungs and start chittering. To each its private void, in a confinement growing tighter the bigger they get. If a spectral sound is supposed to come from beyond the grave, what word might characterize the babble of embryonic life, the noises of beings too tenuous to out themselves from their shell?<br><br> Owls&#39; otherworldly aura—their keening more an atmosphere than an animal sound—has engendered human superstition: What better shorthand for sinister happenings than their ethereal calls? And yet owls have inspired an altogether different response as well. In antiquity, they were sometimes identified as “human-headed birds.” Their domed head, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/article/how-owls-twist-heads-almost-360-degrees">wide-set eye sockets</a> (enabling binocular vision), and flat facial profile—distinctive within their biological class—are features that map onto a human visage. Whether the mythic depiction of owls as thoughtful, even philosophical, beings stemmed from this semblance alone, who can say?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/03/what-the-crow-knows/580726/">From the March 2019 issue: A journey into the animal mind</a><br><br> Perhaps the inference arose instead from an understanding of owls as active at the close of the customary workday, after nightfall, hours that offer the chance for repose and contemplation. Or perhaps owls&#39; sensitivity to stimuli beyond human ken suggested unfathomed know-how, a shrewd intelligence needed to navigate the dark. Either way, the sagacity of owls has long stood as a categorical anomaly in a world in which to be called “birdbrained” remains an insult.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Whether feared or revered</span> , owls have lately invited scrutiny by science writers and ornithologists eager to explain the birds&#39; acute perceptiveness, their far-flung environments (Antarctica is the only continent where you won&#39;t find owls), and the relationships between the two. In her 2016 best seller, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-hidden-lives-of-owls-the-science-and-spirit-of-nature-s-most-elusive-birds-leigh-calvez/9781632170255?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Hidden Lives of Owls: The Science and Spirit of Nature&#39;s Most Elusive Birds</i></a> , Leigh Calvez focuses on the owls of the Pacific Northwest, sharing her suspenseful nighttime explorations of the biology and behavior of birds ranging in size from the saw-whet owl, which can fit in a teacup, to the imposing great grey owl (known to some as the “Phantom of the North”). The conservationist Jonathan C. Slaght has devoted decades to learning about Blakiston&#39;s fish owl, “a fire hydrant with a six-foot wingspan,” as he puts it. In <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/owls-of-the-eastern-ice-a-quest-to-find-and-save-the-world-s-largest-owl-jonathan-c-slaght/9781250798718?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Owls of the Eastern Ice: A Quest to Find and Save the World&#39;s Largest Owl</i></a> (2020), Slaght yokes science to macho adventure in order to track the “floppy goblin” with electric-yellow eyes into the ice-strewn Primorye region of eastern Russia—a shrinking habitat, as are the owl&#39;s hunting grounds in the waters and riverbanks of some of the coldest tributaries in Japan.<br><br> Two new entries in the owl quest find closer kinship between bird and human, yet remain wary of domesticating the dark&#39;s inhabitants too much. In <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-wise-hours-a-journey-into-the-wild-and-secret-world-of-owls-miriam-darlington/9781953534835?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Wise Hours: A Journey Into the Wild and Secret World of Owls</i></a> , the poet and nature writer Miriam Darlington warns against the urge to “cutify” the birds, noting how readily owls&#39; big, forward-facing eyes convey babyish appeal, not just profundity. She has in mind the owl of meme culture, featured in viral YouTube, Tumblr, and TikTok posts; remixed as fan art on Reddit forums; and available as an avatar option in multiplayer video games. Online, owls star as twee, humanoid knockoffs, and could hardly be further from their cryptic counterparts heard caterwauling in the starlit woods. A tour of the platforms reveals owls peevishly rain-drenched, owls clowning around, powder-puff nestlings pleading for a dangled snack, owls wincing and head-bobbing, owls as the rambunctious companions of domestic pets. The antithesis of otherworldly, these and similarly whimsical, infantilized animal portrayals are, in Darlington&#39;s view, an invitation to rob nature of its vital wildness.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2017/01/what-the-octopus-knows/508745/">From the January/February 2017 issue: What the octopus knows</a><br><br> Yet her project to preserve owl awe doesn&#39;t stop her from recruiting the birds to therapeutic ends. Darlington&#39;s adult son falls ill, and the narrative of his diagnosis and treatment (a “perma-drone of worries”) fastens itself to her journey into the insomniac sphere of owls in a season of family crisis. Midway between divesting owls of adorability and asserting their status as a marvel of nature, Darlington finds they have a role to play as her own personal gargoyles: They serve as forbidding beings that externalize the author&#39;s anxieties, helping her to either wing those fears away or confront them.<br><br> The deftness of owls&#39; senses might be regarded as “its own breed of genius.”<br><br> Jennifer Ackerman, internationally beloved by birders as the author of two popular books about avian intelligence— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-bird-way-a-new-look-at-how-birds-talk-work-play-parent-and-think-jennifer-ackerman/9780735223035?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Bird Way: A New Look at How Birds Talk, Work, Play, Parent, and Think</i></a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-genius-of-birds-jennifer-ackerman/9780399563126?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Genius of Birds</i></a> —supplies a more hardheaded assessment of owls, as well as of owl worship, in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/what-an-owl-knows-the-new-science-of-the-world-s-most-enigmatic-birds-jennifer-ackerman/9780593298886?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>What an Owl Knows: The New Science of the World&#39;s Most Enigmatic Birds</i></a> . She locates her owls in the vacant lots of suburban Maringá, in southern Brazil; aloft in hawthorn and chokecherry forests in western Montana; in rehab for roadside injuries in Minnesota; in a limestone quarry in Maastricht, a municipality of the Netherlands. Her investigations lead her to question: How smart are owls, really, and why have they come to stand for the supernatural solemnity of a world beyond us?<br><br> As Ackerman has previously relayed, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/bird-brains-are-far-more-humanlike-than-once-thought/">startling findings have emerged</a> from the study of ornithological cognition over the past two decades. Researchers have discovered that, despite the lack of a layered cerebral cortex, the brains of several avian lineages permit complex feats of memory, logic, recognition, even math. Populations of corvids (crows, rooks, ravens, kindred others) are today famed for tool use, problem-solving, and seemingly ritual responses to their dead. American crows will congregate in cawing mobs around the lifeless bodies of birds of their same species, and later avoid food found in the area. Pinyon jays can remember each of a thousand spots where they once stashed a seed. European magpies pass the mirror test: They can recognize themselves as individuals. Some parrots&#39; language facility far exceeds mimicry. When trained in a lab, pigeons—surely the birds most impugned as automatons—turn out to be <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/23/science/pigeons-can-learn-higher-math-as-well-as-monkeys-study-suggests.html">on par with primates</a> in their counting ability (able to order arrays of objects, from a single object, to a pair, to a trio).<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Ackerman wants to know</span> what the latest science says about how owl species stack up against the cleverest birds. In relation to their body size, owls have large brains, an anatomical characteristic thought to have evolved in tandem with “parental provisioning” of offspring. Indeed, owl nestlings hatch before they can hunt or scavenge, dependent on food supplied by adults to provide the energy their brain tissue needs to grow. Yet for the most part, the brainpower of owls is enchained to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/07/light-noise-pollution-animal-sensory-impact/638446/">the activity of their senses</a> , rather than to the sort of intelligence found in birds that display inventiveness, selfhood, superior powers of recall, or numeracy. Some 75 percent of an owl&#39;s cortexlike forebrain is dedicated to hearing and vision, faculties so astounding in range and exactitude that they might seem, to us, a variety of natural magic.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/07/light-noise-pollution-animal-sensory-impact/638446/">From the July/August 2022 issue: How light and noise pollution confound animals&#39; senses</a><br><br> Owl species deemed “eared” or “horned” don&#39;t actually have external ear pinna the way we do, or bony horns like antelope. The flareable tufts of feathers, called “plumicorns,” they sport atop their head might be used to gesture to other owls, or perhaps to help conceal an owl by breaking up its rounded outline, making it appear more like the stump of a rough or broken branch. Though their true ears are mere apertures hidden under their feathers, owls&#39; reactivity to sound has few equivalents in the animal kingdom. The great grey owl can not only pick up the swish of a vole&#39;s footfall coming from a passage cored into a snowbank, but also figure out the elevation of the sound source, so as to strike through the snow and hit that very point. In some owl species, a portion of the hearing nerve branches into the optical lobe of the brain, which scientists speculate could mean that these owls form a visual signal of something heard but out of sight.<br><br> Owls see well in the dimmest conditions, and some species have retained photoreceptor rods that also make them sensitive to ultraviolet light—they are able to see colors that we cannot. Eurasian eagle owls exploit this part of their visual spectrum by having patches of neck plumage that are brightened by reflecting UV light, markings germane to displays of rivalry. Their young also have UV-reflective blotches inside their throat, prominent cues when the eagle owlets gape for food.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">For Ackerman,</span> the deftness of owls&#39; senses might be regarded as “its own breed of genius”—a supremely adaptive gift—though she recognizes that scientists rarely conceive of animal intelligence this way, finding evidence instead in exceptional behavior that conveys some kind of mental nimbleness or surplus. And owls do engage in some types of activity coded as “smart”: Ackerman reports on this repertoire too. Owls are curious about novelty in their environment—one reason they are prone to getting trapped in pipes, hay blowers, and ventilation shafts, which they gamely explore. Little owls can tell groups of people apart, tolerating farmers but fleeing at a glimpse of ornithologists, who catch and band them.<br><br> Though owl faces may seem static, some species flex and refashion the feathered discs around their eyes to reflect states of alertness or relaxation. Owls, especially juvenile ones, play. They also learn: Great horned owls spend about six months with their parents developing dexterities that will aid their survival, including how to fly through tightly set tree canopies, and how to pounce and kill. Compared with adults, young barn owls <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/sciencemain/stuff-dreams-owlets-sleep-human-babies-6c10945743">experience long spells of REM sleep</a> , the part of the sleep cycle associated with vivid and emotion-laden dreams in humans. If barn owlets dream, researchers suspect that those dreams help cement skills they acquire in the twilight, just as, when mice fall into REM sleep, the rodents enter a period of mental processing associated with learning to take cover from birds of prey (among them, owls).<br><br> Indeed, if we get beyond the emblematic wisdom of owls, we might come to recognize their most anthropomorphic quality—their versatility. Owls have unintentionally migrated as stowaways on ships and flourished in new territory. Corridors of agricultural land have facilitated their dispersal too. A few species have acclimatized remarkably well to our architecture and infrastructure, thriving in stables and belfries, occupying dugouts by causeways, roosting by the hundreds in city squares or in cemeteries (where grave sites, laid with edible votives, attract rodents).<br><br> Male burrowing owls have been documented festooning their earthen tunnels with decorative bits of potato, nubs of concrete, corncobs, old gloves, and stolen fabric (red, white, blue, green, in order of preference)—small treasuries underground. Camera traps have also revealed owl food sources to be more diverse than was once thought. They don&#39;t just eat mice, fish, amphibians, and insects, but will also scavenge for carrion, picking meat from dead dolphins and decomposing crocodiles on the shoreline, and stripping quills from the carcasses of crested porcupines to get at the flesh. The largest owl species will hunt other birds (including owls), and go after skunks, fawns, even cats.<br><br> Ultimately, Ackerman concludes that owls do not warrant their storied eminence as recondite knowledge keepers. Nor are they crow-witted by the standards of modern science. Owls are opportunists. When <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/02/flaco-owl-new-york-instinct-learning-hunting/673217/">Flaco, an eagle owl</a> , first escaped from the Central Park Zoo in New York, his flight muscles were not yet strong enough to support flying farther than four blocks, and he bumbled his landings. For a decade he&#39;d lived off hand-cut meat and slaughtered mice.<br><br> Today Flaco hunts his own vermin, and ranges artfully in the north end of Central Park. Bird-watchers praise the preservation of the wildness within him, despite his long captivity. What proves most bewitching about Flaco, described in his zoo days as “pudgy” and “grumpy,” is how swiftly he has freed himself not only from his enclosure but from performative charm. Owls might yet be our alter egos in more than their ability to prosper in a diversity of habitats. What animal more readily accommodates our deep need to swivel between symbolisms, now hooting their summons to our dark and powerful instincts, now strutting and fluffing their appeal to our sense of whimsy? The duality of owls: as Janus-faced as we are.<br><br> <small><em>This article appears in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/toc/2023/09/">September 2023</a> print edition with the headline “Owls Aren&#39;t That Smart.”</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/owl-senses-smart-animal-intelligence/674769/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/owl-senses-smart-animal-intelligence/674769/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[My Mom Will Email Me After She Dies]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> It&#39;s common now for people to linger as digital ghosts after they die, transforming the nature of loss. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/XH3zhqP1XLT5YiwJs9jsdkCsUGQ=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/grieving_two_horz/original.jpg" alt="花下智能手机的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/《大西洋月刊》插图。 Sources: Getty.</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br> When my mom makes our family Christmas cookies, she no longer needs a recipe. Instead, we stand side by side in the kitchen while I follow her muscle memory, rolling Russian tea cakes in powdered sugar and pressing the bottoms of forks into the dough balls for chocolate crinkle cookies. But my mom is Type A to a <em>t</em> : She&#39;s scanned the pages of step-by-step instructions and keeps them organized on her Google Drive, just in case. And she&#39;s already made sure that, when she dies—whenever that awful day might come—the folder containing all of these recipes will get sent directly to me.<br><br> Technically, the cookie recipes will be part of a larger posthumous digital delivery, arriving in my inbox courtesy of Google&#39;s Inactive Account Manager. They will reach me three months after my mom&#39;s departure—a time frame she selected after doing a regular review of her privacy settings earlier this year (like I said, Type A). With the cookie recipes will come the rest of her Google Drive, containing information including a list of account passwords, and all of her emails. This means there will be a December day when, instead of standing in the kitchen with my mom, I&#39;ll be standing with her digital ghost. I&#39;ll have mourned her physical passing, but will still be able to summon a part of her via my phone, propped up against the flour with one of many smudged and annotated recipe scans on display.<br><br> On this day, I expect I will grieve again. As the author Marisa Renee Lee <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/04/us-covid-grief-one-million-deaths/629533/">noted</a> in this magazine last year, “Grief is the repeated experience of learning to live after loss.” Today, with our ever-expanding digital and technological reach, loved ones left behind must encounter more reminders of that loss than ever before. Memory endures through the email accounts still collecting marketing messages, the Facebook arguments frozen in time, the iPad that continues to uselessly ping about an overdue library book. Left unattended, these digital assets float aimlessly in the internet&#39;s ether. To have control over them presents the inheritor with a challenging personal quandary: Do they take advantage of the weird comfort these digital remains can provide, sinking into an in-between world where the person who died still feels alive, in small pixelated ways? Or do they shut it all down and accept a second death?<br><br> Estate lawyers have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/05/the-social-media-will-an-expert-guide-to-your-digital-afterlife/257112/">long encouraged</a> clients to account for their digital property, but no one has come up with an emotional road map for the burden of inheriting these things. Some logistical matters will only reveal themselves when it&#39;s too late, forcing widows like Ashley Reese to take their grief to the Apple store.<br><br> “I had a weird breakdown,” Reese told me. Her husband, Robert Stengel, died from peritoneal mesothelioma in December at the age of 34. He left behind a comprehensive list of accounts and passwords, and among the things Reese inherited were his AirPods. It was seven months before she felt ready to resurrect his Apple Watch, which she brought to the Apple store for troubleshooting. An employee told her she was wearing it wrong. “I couldn&#39;t do it,” she recalled. “I&#39;m just like, &#39;I&#39;m sorry, this is not mine; it&#39;s my dead husband&#39;s.&#39;”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/10/five-stages-complicated-grief-wrong/671710/">Read: There are no “five stages” of grief</a><br><br> More so than ever before, it is possible for someone to live on through these digital shadows. In addition to holding on to his AirPods and Apple Watch, Reese still keeps her iMessage conversation with Stengel pinned to the top of the Messages app—she once accidentally sent him a text, and tried to unsend it when she realized. When she wants to watch something on Hulu, she can still select his profile. When she opens up YouTube, the algorithm still recommends <em>Succession</em> recaps or fight-scene compilation videos, the things Stengel would be watching if he were alive. When she&#39;s really missing him, she&#39;ll open up his camera roll, and look at one of the last pictures he took—a photo of Reese in his hospital room, unaware that she was being snapped. “This is just psychic damage every day,” she said.<br><br> Lingering in someone&#39;s posthumous digital presence can be as painful as it is comforting, and comes with unexpected revelations. “You don&#39;t want to read too much,” Marie, a woman whose mother died from ovarian cancer last fall, told me. (Marie asked to withhold her last name in order to speak about her family.) Her mom was proactive about her end-of-life plans, going so far as to order her own headstone before she died. She left Marie with her phone, and a list of passwords for all of her accounts. Looking through the device in the days after her mother&#39;s death, Marie found a text thread where her mom had been venting to a friend about a fight they&#39;d had. Marie discovered a Twitter account that her mom had apparently used to spar with right-wingers online—Marie had always thought her mother was as conservative as these opponents. Her Spotify was also revealing: “She listened to so much Taylor Swift, and I had no idea she liked Taylor Swift.”<br><br> Family and friends, themselves grieving, will send text messages to Marie&#39;s mother&#39;s phone. They say they miss her, hoping the sentiment somehow reaches her in the great beyond. Marie reads them. “It&#39;s a nice reminder that she was important to people,” she told me. To know her mother lives on in the thoughts and memories of others is a comfort, one she can now easily access through a screen. Technology like this, which can document a previously intangible part of a person&#39;s legacy, is a gift. It&#39;s also extremely fragile.<br><br> Websites shut down, accounts get hacked, devices break. It&#39;s not safe to assume that direct-message conversations and other social-media memories will be there forever. “My current plan is to just try to do as many digital copies of things as possible,” Reese told me. She has 10 years&#39; worth of messages with Stengel, and plans to back them up on her computer, in Google Drive, and to her iCloud. “I would be absolutely devastated if I lost that stuff.”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/03/how-to-talk-about-grief-support/673232/">Read: What losing two children taught me about grief</a><br><br> At the same time, these digital spaces can help combat another inevitability: that, as the months go by, Reese will start to forget. “I have this compulsion now where if I have any thought about Rob or any memory, I&#39;ll immediately open my Notes app and write it down,” she said, “to remind myself of who I was and who he was, and make sure all those [memories] are intact.”<br><br> It&#39;s tempting not to think about death, choosing instead to be walloped by grief&#39;s right hook one day out of nowhere. Even when my mom let me know about the plans for her Google account, fearing I&#39;d receive an email notification and panic, she didn&#39;t use the word <em>dead</em> . We both knew what she meant, though, and now that I know what awaits me, the records of our digital interactions have more meaning. The Wordle scores texted back and forth, the DMs about our favorite Instagram-famous dog, even the hokey e-cards we still send each other on holidays—these things no longer feel like just more clutter in a digital abyss. Someday, they&#39;ll be the only thing that&#39;s left.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/grief-digital-assets-posthumous-technology/674964/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/grief-digital-assets-posthumous-technology/674964/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Never Tweet]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>特朗普的扩音器又回来困扰他了。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hlQelfIbUlM0junmRSxbP9YxrJY=/0x0:4162x2341/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_869760894/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普讲话" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>曼德尔·颜/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>还记得唐纳德·特朗普发推文吗？当然可以！这位第 45 任总统一次以 280 个字符的帖子吸引了全世界的关注，直到两年半前他被停职。他利用这个平台进行恶搞、骚扰和撒谎。他放大了阴谋论者和他们的观点。他与不稳定的核世界大国对抗，并向否认选举的人讲述了 1 月 6 日在国家广场举行的抗议活动：“去那里，会很疯狂！”这正是我们公众所能看到的。<br><br>今天早些时候，一份未密封的法庭意见显示，为特别检察官杰克·史密斯工作的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/09/us/politics/trump-twitter-account-search-warrant.html">检察官</a>在一月份获得了搜查令，可以访问 @realDonaldTrump 目前处于休眠状态的帐户，也许是为了了解幕后发生了什么（如果有的话）——用户看不到的消息或草稿。根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://static.foxnews.com/foxnews.com/content/uploads/2023/08/gov.uscourts.cadc_.39513.1208541751.0.pdf">意见</a>，搜查令“指示推特提供”与特朗普账户相关的数据和记录。该公司最初拒绝遵守，因为搜查令中包含一项条款，禁止 Twitter 通知特朗普政府已发布搜查令。在被藐视法庭并被罚款 35 万美元后，Twitter 最终交出了这些信息。<br><br>据我采访过的专家称，搜查令看起来很简单，而且保密要素在刑事调查中很常见，检察官担心证据被销毁或处理不当。 （如果特朗普收到警告，他可能会删除史密斯希望找到的任何内容。）值得注意的是，Twitter 经常收到政府的信息请求，有时甚至会遵守政府的信息请求。 <em>Rest of World</em> 4 月份的一份报告<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://restofworld.org/2023/elon-musk-twitter-government-orders/">显示</a>，在埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 的领导下，该公司“收到了 971 项政府要求，并完全遵守了其中 808 项要求”。当然，特朗普的推特账户不是普通的推特账户，对这位前总统的指控——涉及处理机密材料以及涉嫌试图阻挠权力和平移交——都是非同寻常的。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">阅读：为什么埃隆杀死了那只鸟</a><br><br>加州大学伯克利分校法学教授奥林·科尔 (Orin Kerr) 告诉我：“通过在线账户寻找阴谋证据是很常见的。” “如果你抛开这种令人震惊的事实，这种情况发生在一位前总统身上，这是有道理的。他们正在调查一起犯罪行为，而他肯定经常使用推特。”<br><br>史密斯的逮捕令引发了各种各样的问题，比如特别检察官可能在寻找什么，以及检察官在访问前总统的账户时可能会看到什么。<br><br>调查人员会梳理特朗普的直接信息吗？是否可以从与 @realDonaldTrump 关联的 IP 地址中收集有用的信息？检察官可能还想确定发送某些推文的具体设备，以便将它们与特朗普更紧密地联系起来：特朗普在 2019 年<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/16/trump-scavino-1327921">告诉</a><em>Politico</em> ，虽然他“通常”自己写推文，但他的助手丹·斯卡维诺有时会提供帮助。<br><br> “最终，我们只是不知道史密斯得到了什么，”科尔说。 “有一些暗示认为他们正在进行关键词搜索，这可能意味着检察官无法访问所有内容，但我们只是不知道。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trump-indictment-gop-jan-6/674895/">阅读：特朗普对民主的威胁现在是系统性的</a><br><br>当然，人们对世界上最多产、最重要的推特用户之一如何在幕后使用该应用程序感到好奇。理论上，特朗普未发送的推文草稿可以用作证据，尽管我们根本不知道史密斯是否拥有它们。唐纳德·特朗普以避开包括电子邮件在内的大多数形式的数字通信而闻名，并且<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2023/01/trump-has-reportedly-discovered-the-modern-magic-of-texting.html">最近才</a>开始发短信，他是否直接向人们发送消息？如果不是，他的直接消息收件箱可能不太有趣；特朗普恢复的账户在该平台上只有51名关注者，其中大多数是官方账户和家庭成员，并且已经关闭了私信，这意味着除非总统回复他们，否则外界无法发起联系。<br><br>正如克尔指出的那样，不能保证挖掘特朗普臭名昭著的账户会产生任何实质性的东西：“如果没有直接消息，那里可能没有很多证据。”检察官完全有可能只是获得了搜查令，帮助将特朗普的推文作为法庭上的证据：如果问题被提出来，建立一个官方的监管链将消除对任何特定推文是否实际存在的怀疑。<br><br>关于特朗普推特账户的搜索，有很多我们不知道、也可能永远不会知道的事情。如果你知道我不是一名律师，你不会感到惊讶，而只是一名沉迷于 Twitter 的科技作家，已经报道该平台十多年了。但我相信，任何人都应该从今天的新闻中吸取一个无可争议的教训：永远不要发推文。 （特别是如果你认为自己有可能最终陷入联邦检察官指控你密谋欺骗政府的情况的话。）如果特别检察官发现特朗普账户中埋藏着确凿无疑的证据，那么公众将面临更大的风险。挖掘工作将是特朗普十多年来的数字夸夸其谈的直接结果。他对这个平台的痴迷导致了这一刻。它标志着特朗普推特账户的演变，从好奇心变成武器，最后变成合法目标。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 22:40:03 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/trump-twitter-account-special-counsel-search-warrant/674969/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/trump-twitter-account-special-counsel-search-warrant/674969/</item></channel></rss>